Think deeply about when cyclomatic complexity is a misleading metric and what it fails to capture. The standard critique involves switch statements: a function with a 20-case switch statement has a cyclomatic complexity of 21, but if each case is a one-liner with no nested logic, most developers would not consider it complex or hard to understand. Cognitive complexity addresses this by not penalizing flat switch statements at the same rate as nested conditionals, but it introduces its own problems.

Reason through the following failure modes of cyclomatic complexity as a quality signal. First, the switch statement problem: when is a large switch a legitimate and readable dispatch mechanism versus a violation of the Open-Closed Principle that should be refactored to polymorphism? How should a static analyzer distinguish between these cases, given that it has no semantic knowledge of the business domain? Second, the guard clause pattern: a function with 10 early return guard clauses has a cyclomatic complexity of 11 and yet is typically considered more readable than an equivalent function with deeply nested if-else blocks. Should the analyzer penalize guard clauses? Third, method chaining and fluent interfaces: a long method chain in Python or JavaScript has complexity of 1 but may be very hard to debug and test. Fourth, comprehensions and functional style: a complex nested list comprehension in Python has low cyclomatic complexity but high cognitive load. Fifth, generated code: auto-generated serialization code may have very high cyclomatic complexity but requires no human maintenance. How should a quality tool handle these cases — through suppression annotations, through distinguishing file types, or through a fundamentally different metric? Propose a concrete policy for each failure mode.
